doc.previous: Oleo struts have been in use for many decades. [8] Oleo-pneumatic shock absorber technology has continued to be refined, for example with US patent 2959410 A in 1960). [9]
after: Pneumatic systems like the oleo strut generally have long operating lives, and the construction is not unusually complex for maintenance purposes. [10]

An oleo strut consists of an inner metal tube or piston, which is attached to the wheel axle, and which moves up and down in an outer (or upper) metal tube, or cylinder, that is attached to the airframe. The cavity within the strut and piston is filled with gas (usually nitrogen, sometimes air â especially on light aircraft) and oil (usually hydraulic fluid), and is divided into two chambers that communicate through a small orifice.
